      • NULL_HATCH_CONFIDENCE

        private final double NULL_HATCH_CONFIDENCE
        The confidence level of not reaching the scoring potential when computing the optimal number of null hatch panels E.g. A value of 0.8 means that an alliance would be able to score more, if they weren't "capped" by the null hatch panels, in 20% of the matches they play. Conversely, the number of hatch panels would benefit them in 80% of the matches they play. Note that if this value is low, the alliance may not be able to place hatch panels at a rate that matches their cargo cycling, thus also being detrimental.
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • MONTE_CARLO_ITERATIONS

        private final int MONTE_CARLO_ITERATIONS
        The number of Monte Carlo simulation iterations to run to compute standard deviations of functions. A larger number of iterations generally provides greater accuracy.
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • bestStartingLevels

        private int[] bestStartingLevels
        Denotes the best HAB levels to start from at the beginning of the match in order to maximize points earned. Positions correspond to the alliance member position. Assumes that no more than two robots can start from HAB level 2.

      • bestClimbLevels

        private int[] bestClimbLevels
        Denotes the best HAB levels to climb at the end of the match in order to maximize points earned. Positions correspond to the alliance member position. Assumes that no more than two robots can climb HAB level 2 and no more than one robot can climb HAB level 3.

      • avgSampleSize

        private double avgSampleSize
        The average number of scout entries made for each team in the alliance

      • bestSandstormGamePieceCombo

        private java.lang.String bestSandstormGamePieceCombo
        A string denoting the game pieces each member of the alliance should start with in order to maximize points earned. An "H" refers to a hatch panel, while a "C" refers to a cargo. The position of each character corresponds to the alliance member position.

      • calculateStdDevTeleOpPoints

        private double calculateStdDevTeleOpPoints(java.util.ArrayList<java.util.ArrayList<java.util.HashMap<java.lang.String,java.lang.Double>>> allianceSimulationValues)
        Calculates the standard deviation of all tele-op predictions, excluding those found in endgame, through a simulated and randomized data set
        Parameters:
        allianceSimulationValues - Set of simulated expected values for an alliance, randomly generated from a Normal distribution. Each element of the set is an ArrayList with three HashMaps, corresponding to the metric values of a team on the alliance. These values are used to simulate the standard deviation.
        Returns:
        The standard deviation in the predicted number of tele-op points, given the input values

      • generateMonteCarloSet

        private java.util.ArrayList<java.util.ArrayList<java.util.HashMap<java.lang.String,java.lang.Double>>> generateMonteCarloSet(int numIterations)
        Generates a specified number of Monte Carlo simulations of match values for the teams in the current alliance
        Parameters:
        numIterations - Number of simulations to create
        Returns:
        An array with elements representing the result of a Monte Carlo simulation. Each simulation result is an array of three HashMaps, each representing the values of a team in a match, randomly selected from the team's Normal distribution for that metric.

      • calculateOptimalNullHatchPanels

        private void calculateOptimalNullHatchPanels(double confidenceLevel)
        Calculates the optimal number of null hatch panels to place on the cargo ship, based on the alliance's average hatch panel output and its variability. Skews towards the optimistic estimate of hatch panels placed, so it is unlikely that a point "cap" is reached by the alliance if it only scores hatch panels on the cargo ship.
        Parameters:
        confidenceLevel - The confidence level of the t confidence interval created. A higher confidence results in a higher optimistic prediction and lower cap, at the expense of not having enough hatched bays on the cargo ship to place cargo in. A lower confidence results in a higher cap, which means the alliance may run out of hatch panel scoring opportunities.
